# .rules — `agent` (OSS)

> Single source of truth for this repo. AI assistants (Claude, Gemini, Codex/others) and humans
> must read and follow this file. `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and `GEMINI.md` all point here.

## What this repo is
The **open-source** eBPF node agent that observes and secures Kubernetes workloads, purpose-built
to understand **GPU/AI inference** workloads. **Apache-2.0, public.** Open-core pair with the
private `agent-cloud` control plane.

## Stack & tooling
- Language: **Rust**.
- eBPF framework: **`aya`** (pure Rust). **NOT Wasmtime** — that was a different, abandoned idea.
- Layout: **Cargo workspace** (`Cargo.toml` with `members = ["crates/*"]`).
- k8s client: `kube-rs`. Scaffold from `aya-template`.
- Model structure after: `bpfman/bpfman` (Rust+Aya+k8s — closest match), `cilium/tetragon`,
  `falcosecurity/falco`.

## Target crate layout
```
crates/common    shared #[repr(C)] event types — the contract (kernel ⇄ userspace ⇄ cloud). The spine.
crates/ebpf      eBPF programs (no_std, compiled to BPF): kprobes/tracepoints/LSM
crates/agent     userspace binary: loads eBPF, reads ring buffer, enriches, alerts
crates/enrich    k8s metadata enrichment via kube-rs (cgroup → container → pod/namespace)
crates/rules     detection engine
crates/exporter  ship events to the control plane (gRPC/proto)
xtask            build orchestration (compile eBPF + run)
```

## The open-core contract (critical)
- This OSS repo **NEVER** imports `agent-cloud`. Dependencies point one way: **cloud → OSS**.
- The contract = the `common` crate's `#[repr(C)]` event types + the gRPC/proto schema. It lives
  **here**. Keep it stable, `no_std`-compatible, dependency-light.
- The agent must be **fully usable self-hosted with zero cloud**.

## Conventions
- `cargo fmt` + `cargo clippy` clean. eBPF crate is `no_std`; userspace is normal.
- eBPF programs must pass the verifier; get correctness before performance.
  - **Build events in place in the reserved ring-buffer slot and zero the whole slot first**
    (`write_bytes(.., 0, ..)`); never build on the stack and copy. The verifier tracks provenance
    per byte and rejects an uninitialized (incl. padding) byte reaching `bpf_ringbuf_submit` as
    *invalid indirect read from stack*. Keep `#[repr(C)]` event types **padding-free** (order
    `u64`s first) and guard the layout with `const _: () = assert!(size_of::<T>() == …)`.
  - **Capture stable identity in-kernel, at event time** — `cgroup_id`, `mnt_ns_inum`, and the
    `bpf_ktime_get_ns()` timestamp are read while we hold the `task_struct` (the only moment they're
    guaranteed to exist). Userspace post-resolution is inherently racy.
  - **Ring-buffer size must be a power of two and a page multiple**, validated in the loader before
    `bpf_map_create` (else `-EINVAL` with no diagnostic).
- Userspace must never block the ring-buffer drain on enrichment — see **Cold-start & re-sync**.
- **Boot preflight:** verify BTF present, cgroup v2, kernel ≥ 5.8, and read
  `/sys/kernel/security/lsm` — if `bpf` is absent, LSM enforcement (M6) can't attach, so log a
  glaring `WARN` and degrade to `bpf_send_signal` + `cgroup/connect` enforcement.
- The cgroup tree-crawler (M2) runs on a **low-priority background task**, scans only
  `kubepods.slice`, and `statx`es **directories only** (the `cgroup_id` is the dir inode) — never
  leaf files like `cpu.pressure`/`memory.stat`, or a dense node spikes the agent's own CPU.
- Shipped as a Kubernetes **DaemonSet**.

## Cold-start & re-sync (architectural invariant)
When the DaemonSet lands on a node with workloads already running, kernel events arrive in the ring
buffer before the pod cache exists. **Capture and enrichment are two clocks; capture is never gated
on enrichment.**
- **Attach probes first** — accept an initial burst of unenriched events rather than a blind window.
  Missing a boot-time `exec` is a security failure; labeling it late is not.
- **Seed the baseline from `/proc`** (per PID: `cgroup`, `ns/mnt`, starttime, `comm`) — already-
  running pods never fire `exec`; snapshot the running world, then maintain it from exec/exit deltas.
- **Node-scope the kube List** (`fieldSelector=spec.nodeName=$NODE_NAME`) so the initial sync is
  sub-second, not cluster-wide.
- **Cache-miss events park in a bounded, short-deadline resync queue** keyed on
  `(cgroup_id, mnt_ns_inum)` and re-resolve on cache updates; on deadline they emit as explicit
  `Unknown` — never dropped, never silently mislabeled. Queue-full → emit-unenriched + a metric.
- **Make the boundary auditable** — every event carries a `synced` bit (`cold_start` vs `steady`),
  and the readiness probe stays `NotReady` until the `/proc` backfill and initial List complete.
- `synced` and `PodMeta` are **userspace enrichment annotations**, not part of the kernel
  `#[repr(C)]` event ABI.

